<subSubSection id="C36082F2A507FF99FF26FACAFD3EF83E" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC5D179A507FF99FF26FACAFD3EF83E" blockId="13.[151,1436,1402,2008]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="B90E0D6BA507FF99FF26FACAFE8CFA21" bold="true" box="[151,281,1402,1428]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Shell aragonitic; nodulose, granulose, spirally striate or entirely smooth; if smooth or striate then usually with dark axial stripes or axially aligned series of dashes; eroded parietal area may be present, sometimes a small pseudumbilicus; aperture dark with pale spiral band at base (i.e. anterior end) and sometimes another posteriorly. Cephalic tentacles with 2–3 longitudinal black lines, all black, or with broad transverse band at base distal to eye. Operculum paucispiral. Penis with blade-shaped filament (rarely swollen); base usually bifurcate (not so if mamilliform gland absent); usually a single mamilliform gland (sometimes absent, rarely 2); glandular disc of subepithelial glandular tissue usually present; penial vas deferens an open groove or rarely a closed tube. Rod-pieces of paraspermatozoa usually long and straight (rarely small and irregular, or curved). In pallial oviduct egg groove makes a simple loop through albumen gland, straight path through capsule gland and jelly gland; copulatory bursa opens in anterior or posterior position within straight section of pallial oviduct. Spawn a biconvex pelagic capsule with cupola-shaped upper side sculptured by concentric rings, containing single egg; development planktotrophic. Outer marginal radular tooth with flange at inside and usually also at outside of base. Distribution worldwide tropical and warm temperate. (Modified from 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEBAC88A507FF99FD90F8C1FD0AF83E" author="Reid, D. G." box="[545,671,1905,1931]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref71086" refString="Reid, D. G. (2007) The genus Echinolittorina Habe, 1956 (Gastropoda: Littorinidae) in the Indo-West Pacific Ocean. Zootaxa, 1420, 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="2007">Reid 2007</bibRefCitation>
.)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36082F2A507FF9AFF77F827FF76FEF9" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="15" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC5D179A507FF9AFF77F827FF76FEF9" blockId="13.[151,1436,1402,2008]" lastBlockId="14.[151,1436,152,332]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="15" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="B90E0D6BA507FF99FF77F827FED4F804" bold="true" box="[198,321,1943,1969]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Remarks:</emphasis>
The taxonomic history of this genus has been summarized by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEBAC88A507FF99FBABF828FB3FF807" author="Reid, D. G." box="[1050,1194,1944,1970]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref71086" refString="Reid, D. G. (2007) The genus Echinolittorina Habe, 1956 (Gastropoda: Littorinidae) in the Indo-West Pacific Ocean. Zootaxa, 1420, 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="2007">Reid (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. Since the molecular phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7AAAFAA507FF99FEF0F80FFDC1F86D" box="[321,596,1982,2008]" class="Gastropoda" family="Littorinidae" genus="Echinolittorina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B90E0D6BA507FF99FEF0F80FFE61F86D" box="[321,500,1983,2008]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Echinolittorina</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEBAC88A507FF99FD39F80EFC25F86D" author="Williams, S. T. &amp; Reid, D. G." box="[648,944,1982,2008]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="2227 - 2251" refId="ref73800" refString="Williams, S. T. &amp; Reid, D. G. (2004) Speciation and diversity on tropical rocky shores: a global phylogeny of snails of the genus Echinolittorina. Evolution, 58, 2227 - 2251." type="journal article" year="2004">Williams &amp; Reid (2004)</bibRefCitation>
a revised analysis with addition of new sequences (including the new species described herein, making a complete analysis of all 60 known members worldwide) has been published (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEBAC88A504FF9AFD90FF0EFCD7FF6D" author="Williams, S. T. &amp; Duda, T. F." box="[545,834,190,216]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="1618 - 1634" refId="ref73765" refString="Williams, S. T. &amp; Duda, T. F. (2008) Did tectonic activity stimulate Oligo-Miocene speciation in the Indo-West Pacific? Evolution, 62, 1618 - 1634." type="journal article" year="2008">Williams &amp; Duda 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="1341CDFCA504FF9AFCE0FF0EFC0CFF6D" box="[849,921,190,216]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1692,1716]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,692,1668]" captionTargetId="figure-365@6.[152,1435,692,1668]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 1. Molecular phylogeny of all 60 known species of worldwide Echinolittorina (after Williams &amp; Duda 2008), with geographical distributions and subgeneric groups. This is a chronogram, produced by BEAST analysis of sequence data from 28S, 12S and COI genes, which employs Bayesian inference and an uncorrelated, relaxed, log-normal clock; error bars are 95% highest posterior density intervals, and numbers are Bayesian posterior probabilities (see Williams &amp; Duda 2008 for methods). The time calibration of the phylogeny may be underestimated; see Remarks on subgenus Echinolittorina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5318103" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5318103/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Monographs are available of the eastern Pacific species [
<bibRefCitation id="EFEBAC88A504FF9AFEE4FF55FE73FF4A" author="Reid, D. G." box="[341,486,229,255]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="85 - 169" refId="ref71039" refString="Reid, D. G. (2002 b) The genus Nodilittorina von Martens, 1897 (Gastropoda: Littorinidae) in the eastern Pacific Ocean, with a discussion of biogeographic provinces of the rocky-shore fauna. Veliger, 45, 85 - 169." type="journal article" year="2002">Reid 2002b</bibRefCitation>
; as ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C7AAAFAA504FF9AFDAFFF55FD22FF4B" authorityName=", Bandel &amp; Kadolsky" authorityYear="1982" box="[542,695,229,254]" class="Gastropoda" family="Littorinidae" genus="Nodilittorina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90E0D6BA504FF9AFDAFFF55FD22FF4B" box="[542,695,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Nodilittorina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, but 
<taxonomicName id="4C7AAAFAA504FF9AFCB1FF55FAD3FF4A" authority="(Rosewater, 1970)" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Rosewater" baseAuthorityYear="1970" box="[768,1350,229,255]" class="Gastropoda" family="Littorinidae" genus="Austrolittorina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fernandezensis">
<emphasis id="B90E0D6BA504FF9AFCB1FF55FBF1FF4B" box="[768,1124,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Austrolittorina fernandezensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEBAC88A504FF9AFBC4FF55FAABFF4A" author="Rosewater, J." box="[1141,1342,229,255]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="417 - 506" refId="ref71680" refString="Rosewater, J. (1970) The family Littorinidae in the Indo-Pacific. Part I. The subfamily Littorininae. Indo-Pacific Mollusca, 2, 417 - 506." type="journal article" year="1970">Rosewater, 1970</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7AAAFAA504FF9AFA32FF55FE73FE93" authority="(d'Orbigny, 1840)" baseAuthorityName="d'Orbigny" baseAuthorityYear="1840" class="Gastropoda" family="Littorinidae" genus="Austrolittorina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="araucana">
<emphasis id="B90E0D6BA504FF9AFA32FF55FE92FE90" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">A. araucana</emphasis>
(d’Orbigny, 1840)
</taxonomicName>
are now excluded (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEBAC88A504FF9AFD63FEBCFC5EFE93" author="Williams, S. T. &amp; Reid, D. G. &amp; Littlewood, D. T. J." box="[722,971,268,294]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="60 - 86" refId="ref73842" refString="Williams, S. T., Reid, D. G. &amp; Littlewood, D. T. J. (2003) A molecular phylogeny of the Littorininae (Gastropoda: Littorinidae): unequal evolutionary rates, morphological parallelism and biogeography of the Southern Ocean. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 28, 60 - 86." type="journal article" year="2003">
Williams 
<emphasis id="B90E0D6BA504FF9AFCF6FEBCFCE9FE90" box="[839,892,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al</emphasis>
. 2003
</bibRefCitation>
)] and of the Indo-Pacific species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEBAC88A504FF9AFAD2FEBCFF42FEF9" author="Reid, D. G." pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref71086" refString="Reid, D. G. (2007) The genus Echinolittorina Habe, 1956 (Gastropoda: Littorinidae) in the Indo-West Pacific Ocean. Zootaxa, 1420, 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="2007">Reid 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
